  "market_context": "On the monthly/daily NG1! chart, price formed a candle 2 closure near 22,400 with a change in state of delivery, then traded lower in candle 3. After sweeping a prior low without bullish continuation, price retraced back up into a previous fair value gap around 21,400–21,600.",
  "key_observation": "The monthly high was formed by a retracement into a previous fair value gap rather than a manipulation lower. This shallow retracement after expansion confirmed the bearish bias and identified where the monthly wick would form before expansion lower resumed.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Identified a candle 2 closure on the daily near 22,400 with a change in state of delivery, confirming a bearish reversal.",
    "Observed candle 3 trading lower after the reversal.",
    "Checked whether the sweep of a prior low produced a bullish change in state of delivery — it did not, so no bullish manipulation was confirmed.",
    "Noted price retraced into a previous fair value gap around 21,400–21,600 and closed below it, forming the monthly high via retracement rather than manipulation.",
    "Established bearish bias on the next candle given the bearish close, expecting consolidation, manipulation, then distribution lower (AMD).",
    "Anticipated a shallow retracement into the fair value gap zone as the location for the monthly wick to form.",
    "Waited one more candle and observed the retracement with a bearish closure forming the opposing candle, validating the wick location.",
    "Identified expansion lower following the retracement, confirming the expansion-retracement-expansion sequence."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price expanded lower after the retracement into the fair value gap, with the monthly wick forming as anticipated and continuation lower through subsequent consolidations.",
  "lessons": "A monthly/daily high can be formed by a retracement into a previous fair value gap rather than a manipulation sweep. Recognizing this distinction allows anticipation of where the HTF wick will form and confirms the bearish bias for continuation lower.",
